# SPINE — Cursor Rules
# Auto-loaded by Cursor on every prompt. Read this before writing any code.

## What Spine Is
Spine is a behavioral finance app that correlates biometric health data (sleep, HRV, activity)
with spending patterns to predict high-risk financial decision moments and prevent impulsive
spending BEFORE it happens. It is NOT a budgeting app. The core metric is "behavioral tax" —
the extra money a user spends because of poor sleep, stress, or exhaustion.

## Current Stack
- Framework: Next.js 14 (App Router, TypeScript)
- Database: Supabase (PostgreSQL + Auth + RLS)
- Auth: GitHub OAuth via Supabase
- Financial data: Plaid API (PRODUCTION — real bank data)
- Health data: iOS Shortcut → POST to /api/health/submit
- AI: Claude API (Anthropic) — model: claude-sonnet-4-20250514
- Hosting: Vercel (spine-one.vercel.app)
- Styling: Tailwind CSS

## Plaid Status
- ✅ Production approved — use PLAID_ENV=production
- Products enabled: Transactions + Balance
- Use /transactions/sync (NOT /transactions/get)
- Store cursor per plaid_item for incremental syncs

## Absolute Rules — Never Break These
1. NEVER expose SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY or PLAID_SECRET to the client
2. ALL privileged DB operations use service role key server-side only
3. ALL tables have RLS enabled — users only access their own data (user_id = auth.uid())
4. NEVER call Plaid from client-side components — always through API routes
5. NEVER store raw Plaid access tokens in client state
6. Health data and financial data are the most sensitive data in the app — treat accordingly

## Architecture Patterns
- API routes live in /app/api/[route]/route.ts
- Supabase client for server: createClient(url, SERVICE_ROLE_KEY) — server only
- Supabase client for browser: createClient(url, ANON_KEY) — client only
- All API routes validate auth via supabase.auth.getUser() before any data access
- Behavioral risk score is 0–100: LOW (0–30), MEDIUM (31–60), HIGH (61–100)

## Database Tables (Current)
- users → Supabase auth.users (managed)
- plaid_items → user_id, institution_name, access_token, item_id
- transactions → user_id, plaid_transaction_id, amount_cents, posted_at, merchant_name, description
- health_data → user_id, date, sleep_hours, hrv_avg, active_energy (steps), sleep_quality, stress_level
- behavioral_insights → user_id, date, risk_score, insights[], health_summary (jsonb), spending_summary (jsonb)

## AI Layer — "Backbone"
- The AI is branded as "Backbone" in the UI — users see "Backbone says…"
- Never expose "Claude" or "Anthropic" in the UI
- System prompt always injects: current biological state + last 60 days spending + behavioral tax
- Default to claude-sonnet-4-20250514 for all Backbone queries
- Backbone is the name of the feature/product, not an npm package

## Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase in /components
- API routes: kebab-case directories
- DB columns: snake_case
- TypeScript types: PascalCase interfaces in /types
- Environment variables: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE

## Code Style
- TypeScript strict mode — no `any` unless absolutely necessary
- Async/await over .then() chains
- Server Components by default — only use 'use client' when needed
- Error boundaries on all major page sections
- Loading states on all data-fetching components
- Never use alert() — use toast notifications (sonner or similar)

